plot(dune_mds, type='n')
text(dune_mds, 'sp', cex=.5)
 # generate vector of colors 
color_vect = rev(terrain.colors(6))[-1]
points(dune_mds, 'sites', pch=19, 
        col=color_vect[dune.env$Moisture])
legend('topright', paste("Moisture =", 1:5, sep=''), 
        col=color_vect, pch=19)

Nonmetric Multidimensional Scaling is a method that does not measure based off of eigenvectors, so it is not perfect measurements; what this plot does do, however, is portray the variables ordered on a specific number of axes. The point of plots such as this one is to see the strength of the variable’s correlation. The plot above shows that the moisture increases from 1 - 5 going across the x axis, indicating that it is most likely the data set’s most influential variable.

plot(dune_mds, type='n')
 text(dune_mds, 'sp', cex=.5)
 # generate vector of colors 
 color_vect = rev(terrain.colors(6))[-1]
 points(dune_mds, 'sites', pch=19, 
        col=color_vect[dune.env$Manure])
 legend('topright', paste("Manure =", 1:5, sep=''), 
        col=color_vect, pch=19)

This plot of the manure variable is correlated along the y-axis, indicating it is the second-most influential variable for the data set.

The plots show that the moisture is the main indicator of the dune’s vegetation. The second plot means that manure is the second-most influential variable. Looking at these makes me think that a model with solely moisture or a model with both variables will be the most appropriate model.

#Total Model CCA:
total_cca_dunes = cca(dune ~ . , data = dune.env)

RsquareAdj(total_cca_dunes, 100)
## $r.squared
## [1] 0.7106267
## 
## $adj.r.squared
## [1] 0.2215437
anova(total_cca_dunes, permutations = 999)
## Permutation test for cca under reduced model
## Permutation: free
## Number of permutations: 999
## 
## Model: cca(formula = dune ~ A1 + Moisture + Management + Use + Manure, data = dune.env)
##          Df ChiSquare      F Pr(>F)  
## Model    12    1.5032 1.4325  0.028 *
## Residual  7    0.6121                
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
anova(total_cca_dunes, by = 'margin', permutations = 999)
## Permutation test for cca under reduced model
## Marginal effects of terms
## Permutation: free
## Number of permutations: 999
## 
## Model: cca(formula = dune ~ A1 + Moisture + Management + Use + Manure, data = dune.env)
##            Df ChiSquare      F Pr(>F)
## A1          1   0.11070 1.2660  0.221
## Moisture    3   0.31587 1.2041  0.204
## Management  2   0.15882 0.9081  0.570
## Use         2   0.13010 0.7439  0.798
## Manure      3   0.25490 0.9717  0.511
## Residual    7   0.61210
plot(total_cca_dunes, type='n', scaling=1)
orditorp(total_cca_dunes, display='sp', cex=0.5, scaling=1, col='blue')
text(total_cca_dunes, display='bp', col='red')

The total model CCA has an adjusted r-squared of .167 and none of the variables have a significant p-value. As for the plot, it is easy to notice that the Moisture.L is heavily influencing the x-axis (CCA1) and the Manure.L is heavily loaded on the y-axis (CCA2). Use.L is also heavily loaded on CCA1. The model does not seem to be a great fit because none of the p-values are significant.

The moisture only model reveals that this model predicts more of the variance in the data than the model that incorporates all of the explanatory variables. The Moisture.L variable on the plot is heavily along the CCA1 axis. The direction of the arrow shows that certain plants, such as the Juncarti increase as moisture increases, but others are on the other end of the spectrum.

The rest of the plots and anova tests show the individual variables. The final one is Moisture + Manure. The adjusted r-squared for this is 23.6%, the highest r-squared out of all of the models. The model is significant and the plot shows that both of the variables are loaded heavily on respected axes. The takeaway from these CCA Models is that the manure + moisture model is the best one that predicts vegeatation.
